heads and tails
Homonym Number:
Word Class: phrase
Sense Number:
Definition:sleep heads and tails, to sleep, one person's feet at the other's head, to double up in a bed in this manner (when beds are few);  cf tail in, top and tail.
Origin:
Register:
Register 2:
Domain: [none]
Region: [none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes: ca1963 R.M. quoting N.T Moor to sleep head and foot, also used as vt to head and foot (eg children in a bed = to top and tail.
Citations
Date:  15/8/1842
Source:  Piraki Log
Author:
Vol / Page:  143
Edition:  (ed. Anson 1911)
Quote:  Stopped at `Tommy's' [a Maori]. Kikied the `tiners'and the fish. Slept on a Maori mat, wrapped in a blanket: 4 in a bed-place - heads and tails.
Notes:

